length=.name: length=
length=.comment:
Changes the length of this list.

If newLength is greater than the current length, entries are initialized to null.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if the list is fixed-length.

first.name: first
first.comment:
Returns the first element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError. Otherwise this method is equivalent to this.elementAt(0)

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides html5lib/dom.NodeList.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one element in this collection.

iterator.name: iterator
iterator.comment: Returns an Iterator that iterates over this Iterable object.

last.name: last
last.comment:
Returns the last element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError.

length.name: length
length.comment:
Returns the number of objects in this list.

The valid indices for a list are 0 through length - 1.

reversed.name: reversed
reversed.comment: Returns an dart-core.Iterable of the objects in this list in reverse order.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

single.name: single
single.comment:
Returns the single element in this.

If this is empty or has more than one element throws a dart-core.StateError.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and html5lib/dom.NodeList.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the html5lib/dom.NodeList.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

[].comment: Returns the object at the given html5lib/dom.NodeList.[].index in the list or throws a dart-core.RangeError if html5lib/dom.NodeList.[].index is out of bounds.

[]=.comment: Sets the value at the given html5lib/dom.NodeList.[]=.index in the list to html5lib/dom.NodeList.[]=.value or throws a dart-core.RangeError if html5lib/dom.NodeList.[]=.index is out of bounds.

add.name: add
add.comment:
Adds html5lib/dom.NodeList.add.value to the end of this list, extending the length by one.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if the list is fixed-length.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Appends all objects of iterable to the end of this list.

Extends the length of the list by the number of objects in iterable. Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this list is fixed-length.

any.name: any
any.comment: Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the predicate html5lib/dom.NodeList.any.test. Returns false otherwise.

asMap.name: asMap
asMap.comment:
Returns an unmodifiable dart-core.Map view of this.

The map uses the indices of this list as keys and the corresponding objects as values. The Map.keys dart-core.Iterable iterates the indices of this list in numerical order.

List<String> words = ['fee', 'fi', 'fo', 'fum'];
Map<int, String> map = words.asMap();
map[0] + map[1];   // 'feefi';
map.keys.toList(); // [0, 1, 2, 3]

clear.name: clear
clear.comment:
Removes all objects from this list; the length of the list becomes zero.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError, and retains all objects, if this is a fixed-length list.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment: Returns true if the collection contains an element equal to html5lib/dom.NodeList.contains.element.

elementAt.name: elementAt
elementAt.comment:
Returns the html5lib/dom.NodeList.elementAt.indexth element.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.elementAt.index must be non-negative and less than html5lib/dart-core.Iterable.length.

Note: if this does not have a deterministic iteration order then the function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are at least html5lib/dom.NodeList.elementAt.index elements in this.

every.name: every
every.comment: Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the predicate html5lib/dom.NodeList.every.test. Returns false otherwise.

expand.name: expand
expand.comment:
Expands each element of this dart-core.Iterable into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable runs through the elements returned by html5lib/dom.NodeList.expand.f for each element of this, in order.

The returned dart-core.Iterable is lazy, and calls html5lib/dom.NodeList.expand.f for each element of this every time it's iterated.

fillRange.name: fillRange
fillRange.comment:
Sets the objects in the range html5lib/dom.NodeList.fillRange.start inclusive to html5lib/dom.NodeList.fillRange.end exclusive to the given html5lib/dom.NodeList.fillRange.fillValue.

An error occurs if html5lib/dom.NodeList.fillRange.start..html5lib/dom.NodeList.fillRange.end is not a valid range for this.

firstWhere.name: firstWhere
firstWhere.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate html5lib/dom.NodeList.firstWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the html5lib/dom.NodeList.firstWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when html5lib/dom.NodeList.firstWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

fold.name: fold
fold.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each element of the collection with an existing value using the provided function.

Use html5lib/dom.NodeList.fold.initialValue as the initial value, and the function html5lib/dom.NodeList.fold.combine to create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.fold(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment: Applies the function html5lib/dom.NodeList.forEach.f to each element of this collection.

getRange.name: getRange
getRange.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable that iterates over the objects in the range html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.start inclusive to html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.end exclusive.

An error occurs if html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.end is before html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.start.

An error occurs if the html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.start and html5lib/dom.NodeList.getRange.end are not valid ranges at the time of the call to this method. The returned dart-core.Iterable behaves like skip(start).take(end - start). That is, it does not throw exceptions if this changes size.

List<String> colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink'];
Iterable<String> range = colors.getRange(1, 4);
range.join(', ');  // 'green, blue, orange'
colors.length = 3;
range.join(', ');  // 'green, blue'

indexOf.name: indexOf
indexOf.comment:
Returns the first index of html5lib/dom.NodeList.indexOf.element in this list.

Searches the list from index html5lib/dom.NodeList.indexOf.start to the end of the list. The first time an object o is encountered so that o == element, the index of o is returned.

List<String> notes = ['do', 're', 'mi', 're'];
notes.indexOf('re');    // 1
notes.indexOf('re', 2); // 3

Returns -1 if html5lib/dom.NodeList.indexOf.element is not found.

notes.indexOf('fa');    // -1

insert.name: insert
insert.comment:
Inserts the object at position html5lib/dom.NodeList.insert.index in this list.

This increases the length of the list by one and shifts all objects at or after the index towards the end of the list.

An error occurs if the html5lib/dom.NodeList.insert.index is less than 0 or greater than length. An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

insertAll.name: insertAll
insertAll.comment:
Inserts all objects of html5lib/dom.NodeList.insertAll.iterable at position html5lib/dom.NodeList.insertAll.index in this list.

This increases the length of the list by the length of html5lib/dom.NodeList.insertAll.iterable and shifts all later objects towards the end of the list.

An error occurs if the html5lib/dom.NodeList.insertAll.index is less than 0 or greater than length. An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

join.name: join
join.comment:
Converts each element to a dart-core.String and concatenates the strings.

Converts each element to a dart-core.String by calling html5lib/dom.NodeList.toString on it. Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the html5lib/dom.NodeList.join.separator string.

lastIndexOf.name: lastIndexOf
lastIndexOf.comment:
Returns the last index of html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastIndexOf.element in this list.

Searches the list backwards from index html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastIndexOf.start to 0.

The first time an object o is encountered so that o == element, the index of o is returned.

List<String> notes = ['do', 're', 'mi', 're'];
notes.lastIndexOf('re', 2); // 1

If html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastIndexOf.start is not provided, this method searches from the end of the list./Returns

notes.lastIndexOf('re');  // 3

Returns -1 if html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastIndexOf.element is not found.

notes.lastIndexOf('fa');  // -1

lastWhere.name: lastWhere
lastWhere.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when html5lib/dom.NodeList.lastWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

map.name: map
map.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable where each element e of this is replaced by the result of f(e).

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function html5lib/dom.NodeList.map.f will not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating multiple times over the the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function html5lib/dom.NodeList.map.f multiple times on the same element.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
html5lib/dom.NodeList.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to html5lib/dom.NodeList.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If html5lib/dom.NodeList.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of html5lib/dom.NodeList.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

reduce.name: reduce
reduce.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining elements of the collection using the provided function.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.reduce((value, element) => value + element);

remove.name: remove
remove.comment:
Removes the first occurence of value from this list.

Returns true if value was in the list, false otherwise.

List<String> parts = ['head', 'shoulders', 'knees', 'toes'];
parts.remove('head'); // true
parts.join(', ');     // 'shoulders, knees, toes'

The method has no effect if value was not in the list.

// Note: 'head' has already been removed.
parts.remove('head'); // false
parts.join(', ');     // 'shoulders, knees, toes'

An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

removeAt.name: removeAt
removeAt.comment:
Removes the object at position html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeAt.index from this list.

This method reduces the length of this by one and moves all later objects down by one position.

Returns the removed object.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeAt.index must be in the range 0 ≤ index < length.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list. In that case the list is not modified.

removeLast.name: removeLast
removeLast.comment:
Pops and returns the last object in this list.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

removeRange.name: removeRange
removeRange.comment:
Removes the objects in the range html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeRange.start inclusive to end exclusive.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeRange.start and end indices must be in the range 0 ≤ index ≤ length, and start ≤ end.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list. In that case the list is not modified.

removeWhere.name: removeWhere
removeWhere.comment:
Removes all objects from this list that satisfy html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeWhere.test.

An object o satisfies html5lib/dom.NodeList.removeWhere.test if test(o) is true.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
numbers.removeWhere((item) => item.length == 3);
numbers.join(', '); // 'three, four'

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

replaceRange.name: replaceRange
replaceRange.comment:
Removes the objects in the range html5lib/dom.NodeList.replaceRange.start inclusive to html5lib/dom.NodeList.replaceRange.end exclusive and inserts the contents of replacement in its place.

List<int> list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
list.replaceRange(1, 4, [6, 7]);
list.join(', '); // '1, 6, 7, 5'

An error occurs if html5lib/dom.NodeList.replaceRange.start..html5lib/dom.NodeList.replaceRange.end is not a valid range for this.

retainWhere.name: retainWhere
retainWhere.comment:
Removes all objects from this list that fail to satisfy html5lib/dom.NodeList.retainWhere.test.

An object o satisfies html5lib/dom.NodeList.retainWhere.test if test(o) is true.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
numbers.retainWhere((item) => item.length == 3);
numbers.join(', '); // 'one, two'

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

setAll.name: setAll
setAll.comment:
Overwrites objects of this with the objects of html5lib/dom.NodeList.setAll.iterable, starting at position html5lib/dom.NodeList.setAll.index in this list.

List<String> list = ['a', 'b', 'c'];
list.setAll(1, ['bee', 'sea']);
list.join(', '); // 'a, bee, sea'

This operation does not increase the length of this.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.setAll.index must be non-negative and no greater than html5lib/dom.NodeList.length.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.setAll.iterable must not have more elements than what can fit from html5lib/dom.NodeList.setAll.index to html5lib/dom.NodeList.length.

If iterable is based on this list, its values may change /during/ the setAll operation.

setRange.name: setRange
setRange.comment:
Copies the objects of iterable, skipping skipCount objects first, into the range html5lib/dom.NodeList.setRange.start, inclusive, to end, exclusive, of the list.

List<int> list1 = [1, 2, 3, 4];
List<int> list2 = [5, 6, 7, 8, 9];
// Copies the 4th and 5th items in list2 as the 2nd and 3rd items
// of list1.
list1.setRange(1, 3, list2, 3);
list1.join(', '); // '1, 8, 9, 4'

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.setRange.start and end indices must satisfy 0 ≤ start ≤ end ≤ length. If html5lib/dom.NodeList.setRange.start equals end, this method has no effect.

The iterable must have enough objects to fill the range from start to end after skipping skipCount objects.

If iterable is this list, the operation will copy the elements originally in the range from skipCount to skipCount + (end - start) to the range start to end, even if the two ranges overlap.

If iterable depends on this list in some other way, no guarantees are made.

shuffle.name: shuffle
shuffle.comment: Shuffles the elements of this list randomly.

singleWhere.name: singleWhere
singleWhere.comment: Returns the single element that satisfies html5lib/dom.NodeList.singleWhere.test. If no or more than one element match then a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

skip.name: skip
skip.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips the first html5lib/dom.NodeList.skip.n elements.

If this has fewer than html5lib/dom.NodeList.skip.n elements, then the resulting Iterable is empty.

It is an error if html5lib/dom.NodeList.skip.n is negative.

skipWhile.name: skipWhile
skipWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips elements while html5lib/dom.NodeList.skipWhile.test is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable iterates over all elements of this.

As long as the iterator's elements satisfy html5lib/dom.NodeList.skipWhile.test they are discarded. Once an element does not satisfy the html5lib/dom.NodeList.skipWhile.test the iterator stops testing and uses every later element unconditionally. That is, the elements of the returned Iterable are the elements of this starting from the first element that does not satisfy html5lib/dom.NodeList.skipWhile.test.

sort.name: sort
sort.comment:
Sorts this list according to the order specified by the html5lib/dom.NodeList.sort.compare function.

The html5lib/dom.NodeList.sort.compare function must act as a dart-core.Comparator.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
// Sort from shortest to longest.
numbers.sort((x, y) => x.length.compareTo(y.length));
numbers.join(', '); // 'one, two, four, three'

The default List implementations use html5lib/dart-core.Comparable.compare if html5lib/dom.NodeList.sort.compare is omitted.

List<int> nums = [13, 2, -11];
nums.sort();
     nums.join(', '); // '-11, 2, 13'

sublist.name: sublist
sublist.comment:
Returns a new list containing the objects from html5lib/dom.NodeList.sublist.start inclusive to html5lib/dom.NodeList.sublist.end exclusive.

List<String> colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink'];
colors.sublist(1, 3); // ['green', 'blue']

If html5lib/dom.NodeList.sublist.end is omitted, the html5lib/dom.NodeList.length of this is used.

colors.sublist(1);  // ['green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink']

An error occurs if html5lib/dom.NodeList.sublist.start is outside the range 0 .. length or if html5lib/dom.NodeList.sublist.end is outside the range start .. length.

take.name: take
take.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable with at most html5lib/dom.NodeList.take.n elements.

The returned dart-core.Iterable may contain fewer than html5lib/dom.NodeList.take.n elements, if this contains fewer than html5lib/dom.NodeList.take.n elements.

It is an error if html5lib/dom.NodeList.take.n is negative.

takeWhile.name: takeWhile
takeWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that stops once html5lib/dom.NodeList.takeWhile.test is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable starts iterating over the elements of this.

When the iterator encounters an element e that does not satisfy html5lib/dom.NodeList.takeWhile.test, it discards e and moves into the finished state. That is, it does not get or provide any more elements.

toList.name: toList
toList.comment:
Creates a dart-core.List containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

The elements are in iteration order. The list is fixed-length if html5lib/dom.NodeList.toList.growable is false.

toSet.name: toSet
toSet.comment: Creates a dart-core.Set containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

where.name: where
where.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable with all elements that satisfy the predicate html5lib/dom.NodeList.where.test.

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function html5lib/dom.NodeList.where.test will not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating multiple times over the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function html5lib/dom.NodeList.where.test multiple times on the same element.
